<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun1-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>FUN-1 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 3 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Things you should understand and know:
        <ul>
            <li><p>What a plane vector is</p></li>
            <li><p>The formula for the magnitude of a vector</p></li>
            <li><p>Three-dimensional space mathematically</p></li>
            <li><p>When two vectors are perpendicular</p></li>
            <li><p>The vector projection of one vector onto another vector</p></li>
            <li><p>How the cross-product relates to areas and volumes</p></li>
            <li><p>How torque relates to force and position</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>Things you should be able to do:
        <ul>
            <li><p>Perform basic vector operations in two and three-dimensions</p></li>
            <li><p>Express a vector in component form or in terms of unit vectors</p></li>
            <li><p>Write and use the distance formula in three dimensions</p></li>
            <li><p>Write the equations for simple planes and spheres</p></li>
            <li><p>Calculate the dot product of two vectors</p></li>
            <li><p>Determine the direction of a vector</p></li>
            <li><p>Compute a vector projection</p></li>
            <li><p>Calculate the work done by a given force</p></li>
            <li><p>Calculate the cross-product of two vectors</p></li>
            <li><p>Use determinants to calculate a cross-product</p></li>
            <li><p>Find a vector orthogonal to two given vectors</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the area or volume using the cross-product</p></li>
            <li><p>Calculate the torque of a force and a vector</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>You will be assessed on the following criteria:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
              that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
          <li><p>Vector Operations: Perform vector addition, subtraction, and scalar multiplication. Evaluate 
              the magnitude and direction of vectors. Find the dot product and cross product of vectors.</p></li>
          <li><p>Vector Applications: Apply vector concepts to solve real-world problems, such as finding the 
              resultant of two forces, work done by a force, etc.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Given two points in space, P(-1,5,-10) and Q(3,2,4) find the 
          vector connecting them.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>To find the vector connecting two points, subtract the 
        coordinates of the first point from the coordinates of the 
        second point.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>\vec{PQ} = \lt 4, -3, 14 \gt</m></p></answer>
      <solution>
        <p>To find the vector connecting two points, subtract the coordinates 
          of the first point from the coordinates of the second point. So, 
          <m>\vec{PQ} = Q - P = (3,2,4) - (-1,5,-10) = \lt 4, -3, 14 \gt</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>Given two vectors <m>a= \lt 2,2 \gt</m> and <m>b= \lt -1-\sqrt{3},1-\sqrt{3} \gt</m></p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Find the unit vector, <m>\vec{u}</m>, in the direction of <m>a</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>A unit vector has a magnitude of 1. To find it, divide the vector 
          by its magnitude.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\vec{u} = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find the unit vector in the direction of <m>a</m>, 
          we first need to find the magnitude of <m>a</m>. The magnitude is 
          given by <m>|\vec{a}| = \sqrt{2^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{8} = 2\sqrt{2}</m>. 
          Then, we divide the vector <m>a</m> by its magnitude to get the unit vector:
          <m>\vec{u} = \frac{\vec{a}}{|\vec{a}|} = \frac{\lt 2, 2 \gt}{2\sqrt{2}} = \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)</m>.</p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Find the angle between vectors <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>The angle between two vectors can be found using the dot product formula: 
            <m>\cos \theta = \frac{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}}{|\vec{a}||\vec{b}|}</m>.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\theta = \frac{5\pi}{6}</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>To find the angle between vectors <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, we use the 
            dot product formula. First, we find the dot product: <m>\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b} = 
              (2)(-1-\sqrt{3}) + (2)(1-\sqrt{3}) = -2-2\sqrt{3}+2-2\sqrt{3} = -4\sqrt{3}</m>. 
              Next, we find the magnitudes of both vectors: <m>|\vec{a}| = \sqrt{8} =2\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>|\vec{b}| = 
                \sqrt{(-1-\sqrt{3})^2+(1-\sqrt{3})^2} = \sqrt{8} = 2\sqrt{2}</m>. Then, we substitute into the 
                formula: <m>\cos \theta = \frac{-4\sqrt{3}}{(2\sqrt{2})(2\sqrt{2})} = \frac{-4\sqrt{3}}{8} = 
                  \frac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>. Therefore, <m>\theta = \frac{5\pi}{6}</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Find the projection of vector <m>a</m> onto vector <m>b</m>.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>The projection of vector <m>a</m> onto vector <m>b</m> is given by: 
            <m>\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = \frac{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}}{|\vec{b}|^2} \vec{b}</m>.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = \left\lt\frac{3+\sqrt{3}}{2}, \frac{3-\sqrt{3}}{2}\right\gt</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>To find the projection of vector <m>a</m> onto vector <m>b</m>, we use the formula: 
            <m>\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = \frac{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}}{|\vec{b}|^2} \vec{b}</m>. We already found that 
            <m>\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b} = -4\sqrt{3}</m> and <m>|\vec{b}|^2 = 8</m>. Substituting these values, we get: 
            <m>\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = \frac{-4\sqrt{3}}{8} \vec{b} = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \vec{b}</m>. Since 
            <m>\vec{b} = \lt -1-\sqrt{3}, 1-\sqrt{3} \gt</m>, the projection is: 
            <m>\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}(-1-\sqrt{3}, 1-\sqrt{3}) = \left\lt\frac{3+\sqrt{3}}{2}, \frac{3-\sqrt{3}}{2}\right\gt</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>An object weighing 5 lbs is located at the point 
        (2,1,5) and is being pulled by a cable in the direction of (0,-3,-1) 
        with a force of <m>\sqrt{14}lbs</m>.</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the force of the cable on the object.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The force of the cable on the object is given by the product of 
          the force magnitude and the unit vector in the direction of the cable.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\vec{F} = \lt -1, -2, -3 \gt</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>The force of the cable on the object is given by: 
          <m>\vec{F}_{cable} = |\vec{F}| \vec{u}</m>, where <m>|\vec{F}| = \sqrt{14}</m> 
          and <m>\vec{u}</m> is the unit vector in the direction of the cable. The unit vector 
          is: <m>\vec{u} = \frac{\lt 0-2, -3-1, -1-5 \gt}{\sqrt{(0-2)^2 + (-3-1)^2 + (-1-5)^2}} =
             \frac{\lt -2, -4, -6 \gt}{\sqrt{4 + 16 + 36}} = \frac{\lt -2, -4, -6 \gt}{\sqrt{56}} = \frac{\lt -1, -2, -3 \gt}{\sqrt{14}}</m>. 
             Therefore, <m>\vec{F}_{cable} = \sqrt{14} \cdot \frac{\lt -1, -2, -3 \gt}{\sqrt{14}} = \lt -1, -2, -3 \gt</m>. 
        </p></solution>
      </task>  
      <task>
        <statement><p>Give the total force acting on the object.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The total force is the sum of all forces acting on the object.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\vec{F}_{total} = \lt -1, -2, -8 \gt</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>The total force acting on the object is the sum of all forces. Since 
          we have the force from the cable and the force due to gravity, the total force
          is the sum of these forces. The force from the cable is: <m>\vec{F}_{cable} = 
            \lt -1, -2, -3 \gt</m> and the force due to gravity is: <m>\vec{F}_{gravity} = \lt 0, 0, -5 \gt</m>. 
            Therefore, the total force is: <m>\vec{F}_{total} = \vec{F}_{cable} + \vec{F}_{gravity} = 
              \lt -1, -2, -3 \gt + \lt 0, 0, -5 \gt = \lt -1, -2, -8 \gt</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>  
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the area of the triangle with vertices at (-1,0,0), (2,3,0), and (0,4,6).</p></statement>
        <hint><p>The area of a triangle with vertices at <m>\vec{a}</m>, <m>\vec{b}</m>, and <m>\vec{c}</m> is given by: 
          <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2}|\vec{ab} \times \vec{ac}|</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\text{Area} = \frac{27}{2}</m> square units </p></answer>
        <solution><p>Let <m>\vec{a} = (-1,0,0)</m>, <m>\vec{b} = (2,3,0)</m>, and <m>\vec{c} = (0,4,6)</m>. Then: 
          <m>\vec{ab} = \lt 2-(-1), 3-0, 0-0 \gt = \lt 3, 3, 0 \gt</m> and <m>\vec{ac} = \lt 0-(-1), 4-0, 6-0 \gt = \lt 1, 4, 6 \gt</m>. 
          The cross product is: 
          <m>\vec{ab} \times \vec{ac} = \lt 18, -18, 9 \gt</m>. The magnitude of the cross product is: 
          <m>|\vec{ab} \times \vec{ac}| = \sqrt{18^2 + (-18)^2 + 9^2} = \sqrt{324 + 324 + 81} = \sqrt{729} = 27</m>. 
          Therefore, the area is: 
          <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 27 = \frac{27}{2}</m> square units.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <task>
        <statement><p>A snow machine drags a sled along a flat trail.  The tether makes an angle of 
          <m>25^{\circ}</m> with the sled and the tension in the tether is <m>1050 N</m>. How much
          work is done by the machine in pulling the sled 0.7km?
        </p></statement>
        <hint><p>Work is given by the product of the force and the distance moved in the direction of the force.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>W = 735000 \cos(25^\circ) \approx 666,136</m> Nm</p></answer>
        <solution><p>The work done by the machine is given by: <m>W = F \cdot d \cdot \cos(\theta)</m>, where 
          <m>F = 1050 N</m>, <m>d = 0.7 km = 700 m</m>, and <m>\theta = 25^{\circ}</m>. 
          Therefore, <m>W = 1050 \cdot 700 \cdot \cos(25^{\circ}) \approx 735000 \cos(25^{\circ}) \approx 666,136.22</m> Nm.</p></solution>
      </task>  
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
